column6: "In complex of outflows 13/14/15 from Tanabe. Zooming in
column7: there is a pretty nice small N-S red/blue outflow driven by this source. I believe this one. The CARMA-NRO combined data reveals this one in much better detail than Tanabe's NRO-only observations. This CO outflow is cataloged in Takahashi et al. 2008 and Shimajiri et al. 2008 as well."

column6: "This source in also in the outflow complex 13/14/15 in the OMC 2 region. Not assigned any outflows by Tanabe
column7: but it could contribute to the linear redshifted lobe in the south
column8: and perhaps some of the blueshifted emission to its north. Not a certain outflow but can't rule one out either."

column6: "So many red/blue contours in this location. The cluster of protostars could all be driving outflows
column7: so it's hard to see how Tanabe made a confident identification of this protostar with this outflow. It looks like
column8: perhaps the red/blue lobes to the NE of this source are driven by this source
column9: whereas the blue/red contours to the SW may be a new bipolar outflow driven by Spitzer Orion 2293 (IRS 17/MMS 17)"

column6: "This protostar is in the vicinity of the giant blue outflow lobe of Tanabe 25/SMZ 38. But no CO outflow is apparent from this source."

"This Class I protostar is located right in the middle of the HH 2 bow shock / H2 knots. But it appears unrelated to this outflow. There is a lot of redshifted CO here which could be entirely part of the HH 2 flow
column7: or partly driven by a separate outflow coming from this source. No blueshifted CO is apparent."

column6: "Some blue CO in a large arcing structure to the NW. Doesn't look particularly like an outflow."
"HOPS 380 is the 3rd protostar in the group with HOPS 173/174 which may be responsible for Tanabe outflow 36 and H2 flow DFS115. See the entries for HOPS 173/174 for more."
"No evidence for CO outflow around this run of the mill Class I source."
"This source has red/blue lobes on either side in CO
column7: but the blue lobe to the SE is assigned by Tanabe to their Outflow 2 w/ the disk source Spitzer Orion 2450 as the driving source. The morphology of the CO definitely points to HOPS 383 as the more likely source of the blue lobe and perhaps some portion of the red emission to the NW
column8: part of which is in Outflow 1. Stanke et al. 2002 do not assign a driving source to the H2 flow SMZ 2
column9: which consists of 2 H2 knots and an arc of diffuse emission near to the disk source to the south. I believe it's more likely this H2 flow as well as the CO outflow are driven by HOPS 383."

column6: "HOPS 394 is a Class 0 protostar in a region with several outflows (Tanabe 9-12). This source could potentially drive the redshifted CO just to the North
column7: but it seems more likely that is part of the bipolar outflow/H2 outflow driven by HOPS 70 (SMZ 15)."

column6: "Outflow 18 from Tanabe gives the redshifted emission on top of this source to the Spitzer Orion 2236 (classified as Protostar) just to the SW. But HOPS 409 could just as well be driving any of the redshifted emission in this area. Or
column7: perhaps more likely
column8: there is no outflow here and the redshifted emission is just an extension of the cloud."
